The Czech Social Democrats in Prague know neither Voldemort nor the "confectionery".
The new councillors of the capital from the ranks of the ČSSD will obviously have to overcome certain language barriers in order to understand their old-new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague City Council and the city council in general.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz has once "tapped" members of the new ČSSD council a little bit about their mastery of the notorious slang that has become established in recent years when the current coalition partners in Prague were at the helm.
The coded vocabulary, introduced by the Prague political elite in the past era of Mayor Pavel Bém, is borrowed from some of the most famous actors, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, the new councils have been left in the dark about what these new terms mean.
At least that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I don't know".
"I am rather a newcomer to Prague politics", said Lukáš Kaucký, the new councillor for culture, when asked about the test of the "Godfather's vocabulary".
But the councillor Karel Březina - a political veteran - reacted in a similar way.
For example, the term "golf hole".
"That's the only expression you've given me that I use now and then".
"Otherwise, I'm not much of a slang person".
From the vocabulary published by the daily Aktuálně.cz in June this year ahead of the ODS election congress, the editorial board selected six terms, especially those notoriously associated with the Prague magistrate.
The Social Democrats should define the terms "Voldemort", "the biggest golf hole in Prague", "go to the pastry shop", "bull neck", "betray the capital" and "bleach".
Three Prague councillors agreed to the test, and the fourth - Antonín Weinert, the future head of the Prague school system - promised to participate in the discussion at first but then did not even answer the phone.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, rejected the test from the start.
"I don't care about these things and how the bourgeois democrats talk to each other, I don't judge".
"What is important to me is how we understand each other in our programmes", he countered.
As already indicated, Lukáš Kaucký did not seem to realize in the headline mentioned above that the influential businessman and friend of the former mayor of Bém, Roman Janoušek, was being referred to.
The word "Voldemort" doesn't mean anything to Kaucky, and the only word he could correctly say in the test was "the biggest Prague golf hole".
"This is the Blanka tunnel", says Kaucký, adding, for safety's sake: "But I know more from the newspaper".
And jokingly, "I guess I'll have to take a language course".
The "golf hole" is then correctly deciphered as the Blanka tunnel not only by Matador Karel Březina but also by the councilor for environmental issues Lukáš Plachý.
But both social democrats also know who Voldemort is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find him and what it means to go to the pastry shop.
"I think it means going to some Prague restaurant", Plachý is pretty close to solving the puzzle, given that this is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
However, in line with Březina, he claims that he has drawn this knowledge from the newspaper rather than that this vocabulary is his own.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the Community's own resources are used to finance the measures.
"I asked my colleagues, but obviously we don't have that".
"We call each other by our first names, sometimes we use abbreviations or nicknames", says Petr Hulínský, chairman of the Prague ČSSD - nicknamed "Hulda" by his party comrades.
"In school I was called Bříza (Birch), but I don't know if my colleagues call me that", Karel Březina tells us.
The newspaper Deník Aktuálně.cz tried the name and look - it works.
Mr Weinert is a kind "grandfather" to party comrades or less so to the "old man", the deputy Miroslav Poche, who before the elections attracted attention by his party sponsorship activities, is called by some colleagues "Igráček" (a famous Czech Lego figure).
The only thing the Social Democrats allow in their internal party language are nicknames.
Hulínský reportedly doesn't like being called "Hulda", but Deník Aktuálně.cz registered another nickname for the Prague chairman.
His nickname "Doctor of Rubber-Clipping Rights" is allegedly related to the fact that Petr Hulínský obtained his Doctor of Juris degree from the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and has published a brochure
Women who are branded as witches in Burkina Faso usually have some social characteristics in common.
They are more likely to be older, unable to find work - for example, for health reasons, single and childless.
If one of these women "becomes" a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become a danger to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate".
"Young and healthy women are spared because they help out with work and have children", describes a religious sister who cares for more than a hundred women who have been excluded from their communities in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for that reason, I published a pamphlet to stop the "witch hunt".
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso are illiterate", noted the newspaper der Standard, pointing to the dilemma of written instruction.
But the accusation of witchcraft is also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, a neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they doused her with petroleum and simply set her on fire.
The BBC server also reported on this incident.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that it was just a coincidence.
According to their version, it was oil that was set on fire, used for ritual anointing.
After the group tried to "cast out an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by the people here regardless of their education.
The Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Soul-eaters were as dangerous as they are today".
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, the Gambian president has been very involved in the president himself last year.
"President Yahya Jammeh launched a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, claiming that she was involved in her death and that she would now attempt to kill the president himself through black magic".
"He called in shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's bodyguard, forcibly abducted women and men from Gambian villages and took them to the president's farm in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the imprisoned people were forced to drink plant excrement that was hallucinogenic but also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the people arrested did not survive their stay at the farm.
Only under international pressure were the nearly a thousand prisoners released.
Bakala tenant: He uses a furnace to heat the house, but still pays more rent
An elderly male employee is leaving the customer center of the company RPG Byty of "coal baron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm was a briefcase with three new leases for three apartments: his own and the apartments of his daughters and his son, who is serving time.
All three have just had their rents increased as part of the so-called deregulation.
Instead of 3,500 crowns a month, the son will spend 4100 crowns next year on a two-room apartment with a second-class kitchen.
"And there's not even running hot water in the apartment, and you have to heat it in a simple coal oven", he angrily taps his finger at his son's new lease, which he has a power of attorney to sign.
"But what - I signed", he explains half displeased and half resigned.
The citizens' association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and immoral", advises tenants to simply not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7 when it intends to publish a guide on how to deal with such contracts.
But the man just waves.
"One says this, the other that", he makes a grim face.
The Ostrava region is thus becoming a major 'laboratory for deregulation'.
After the New Year, most rental properties in the Czech Republic will face deregulation, as their tenants do not yet pay market-based rent.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this "laboratory" in person.
The RPG waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and already at nine o'clock this Tuesday morning it is packed.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and a pager.
"Rent 2011", a special button on the touch screen lights up.
You type in a few words, and the machine spits out a license plate.
We've barely cracked the number "157", and it's beeping on the big display on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later, it's your turn.
A little later, an elderly couple enter the waiting room to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room apparently does not apply to the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair claims, insurance matters and the like.
From mid-November, the envelopes with the new lease agreements will be flitting into the mailboxes of most tenants of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio in the Ostrava region.
RPG Byty proposes to them in the letters a rent increase of about 15 to 38 percent.
The special counter for new rentals in the customer centre has been open since 18 November.
"The campaign has been going on for a little over a week, which means it's just the beginning", the ladies behind the counter reply after a moment's hesitation when the "client" turns out to be a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former miners' housing is a hot topic.
Before the elections, the deputy speaker of the Ostrava-based ČSSD Lubomír Zaorálek raised the issue quite loudly, no wonder the newspapers are full of it today.
"Twenty years I want them to have a new floor".
"They couldn't even change their toilet glasses", the man mentioned at the outset says.
So far, the employees say, most of the people waiting at the counter are pensioners to see if they really get the promised rent reduction that RPG promises if they sign the special offer on time.
The other tenants who sign the new lease contract before 15 December will also be entitled to a half-reduced February rent.
But so far, the "deregulation switchboard" in Havířov is far from overloaded with demand.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 were due here in 2011", the clerks estimate.
RPG offers individual rental agreements on its websites and on its billboards wherever necessary.
If the parties do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
"This is not intended to be a threat, but should be understood as information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal course of action", RPG states on its website.
"No one goes to court here", says one of the employees of RPG Byty, and a man on the street outside the customer centre agrees with her at least in part.
"I have a pension of 13,000, of which 5,000 is left for food, where should I get the money for a court case", he says.
Then the employee will be unsure.
"Let's see".
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign and people are still waiting", she said.
The regulated rent ends in most of the Czech Republic on New Year's Day 2011 and according to RPG Byty the rent increase is an economic necessity.
"The existing rent levels are not even enough to maintain the housing stock", argues Pavel Klimeš, the director of the housing portfolio of RPG Byty, and - in the opinion of the homeowners - the neglect of the housing stock, which has been criticized by the angry tenants, is the main reason for the rent increase.
While RPG was able to invest EUR 4 billion in the housing units from 2005 to 2010, it is expected to invest EUR 5,2 billion in the four years from 2011 to 2014.
The large LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstered chairs in the Havířov waiting room keeps showing a few red-lit messages.
'The rent increases in 2011 of 15% and less concern 31 200 dwellings, i.e. more than 90% of the dwellings in RPG.'
"This always means no more than CZK 7.50 per square metre per month", reads the LCD screen.
Just 400 apartments in RPG's portfolio increase rents by 38 percent.
'These cases are about the increase in extremely low rents of CZK 19,66 per square metre', RPG argues.
The rent for 2,600 apartments will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive rents up by leaps and bounds, but will be gradual over four to eight years.
Moreover, the company is making a further commitment: all the income from the rent increase (see diagram) will be put back into the dwellings, mainly in thermal savings - in new windows and in thermal insulation.
- but these should primarily benefit those people who sign the agreements on the rent increase.
The architects saw through it - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten with all the amenities: colorful walls, creative furniture, lots of toys, and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace?
This kindergarten has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, whose studios are home to a number of famous Brno buildings, has been counting on the premises for its company's mini-kindergarten from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building.
The company is looking forward to the future, as most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom and the company wants the designers and architects to return to work as soon as possible.
Alongside the possibility of shorter working hours, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees as part of its social programme.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the new legislation is implemented in a way that is consistent with the objectives of the directive.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the Arch.Design staff and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
The financing (grants of CZK 2.8 million) enabled the necessary facilities and equipment to be procured and provided for the qualified staff and operation for a period of two years.
After the funding has been used up (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the mini-nursery at its own expense for a further 3 years.
The preparation of this project took a year, with the help of Economy Rating providing practical assistance in the application process.
The children are cared for by qualified staff on a full-time basis - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, and the kindergarten is open to children of all ages, although most are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only five children are allowed to be present at a time, but several children take turns in the day.
The day care is flexible and tailored to the needs of the parents, and the children of all staff have the same rights in the use of the day care - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care, the content of the programme in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children here not only play, but above all they receive excellent instruction - from basic knowledge to preschool education, and they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What is more, the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can look at the children at any time and thus eliminate the stress of late picking up the children from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
It is no wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relations are also developing here.
Arch.Design thus became one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programmes.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The local inhabitants nicknamed the house "Bone House" for its organic forms.
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures that recall nature and living creatures.
Only when you look closely do you notice that everything is governed by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole facade is even more plastic, dramatic, and the special lighting enhances the brilliance of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and curved shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy wood is used to make window frames, railing, door frames, even viewpoints and ledges.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district, on the busy Passeig de Gracia shopping street, 43 was built by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but he eventually agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló rental house alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created and the use of mosaics on the facade was also his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Soon after its completion, the house was given its organic forms by the local inhabitants, who nicknamed it the "Bone House".
Others called it the "gliding house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is displayed at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique for the time, with drainage channels and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre is already starting to happen with her 45-degree tilt.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building codes of the day and was not swayed by them.
He obtained the city's building permit to begin construction, but the details he gave about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when the city was finished, the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded a remedy.
The council members also found it difficult to accept the fact that the building with its pillars even entered the public sidewalk.
However, no changes were made, on the contrary - just 15 days after the district requested it, Josep Batlló applied for permission to lease the two highest floors of the building - and it was granted promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
The second floor gallery contained a social hall, while the third floor contained the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs up a flight of stairs to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger company could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
Gaudí's renovation of the house provided it with a rather unusual roof and two more floors, in addition to a new facade.
Gaudí's play with light is also impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles that cover the courtyard and the lighthouses.
The combination of these two colors gives all floors of the house maximum light.
He simply applied the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is open to the public.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only this year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the tours were continued, and even extended to other common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
The price of the tour is 16.50 euros, with a 20 percent discount for students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders.
This is more than the entrance fees for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the inhabitants and visit him at home.
