More and more parents want human monitors to keep their kids in check
Fears for their own children are growing, and more and more parents are considering GPS tracking.
The system, originally designed to locate cars, can locate people just as well, which would be helpful in such cases as the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette case, but soon it will be no larger than a wristwatch.
Many people are terrified by the case of Anička, and are looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not a case of spying around, but an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases, such devices can be misused, for example, if you put them in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not seen any such cases".
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons", Pilin adds.
He believes that the child should always know what the box is for and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like wearing such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in deliberately dropping things when they don't want to be controlled".
"Even the cell phones initially raised high expectations among parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices", says Ms. Bočková.
In their view, it is also controversial whether such a device actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the case of planned abductions, the kidnapper almost always checks to see if the child has any electronic devices with him that could be used to locate him".
"Today it's the cell phone".
"If such surveillance devices were to be used more widely, they would also seek them out, as their sale would certainly be accompanied by massive advertising".
"In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, she admits that similar devices can be helpful in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Roberta Čech of RC Monitoring, a company that provides tracking services for both cars and people, the existence of such a device can help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
'The device can be set to indicate the position at certain intervals.'
"Even if it were destroyed immediately, at least the last position of the person concerned is available".
"More expensive devices even have a built-in tiltmeter, which means that if you fall and lie still, the device immediately sends a warning indicating your position", says Mr Čech.
He believes that similar services could also be used on smart mobile phones with navigation, with the help of special software.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they are either matchbox-sized devices that look like trailers or smaller cell phones.
There's always a chance you'll lose them.
