A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than their ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling result of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It's supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can be a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly in men up to 60", explains study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be screened for prostate cancer, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health issues, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients, as well as 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a right index finger shorter than their ring finger.
These men had the same risk of prostate cancer as 19 percent of men with ring fingers and index fingers of the same length.
But for men whose index finger was longer than their ring finger, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men up to age 60, by 87 percent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers mentioned, which are formed at the prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones that the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was only briefly aware of the study, but that he did not think the link between finger length and cancer risk had been "fully established".
