The discovery of an alien species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously considered essential to life.
"This organism has two options".
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow".
"This makes it quite special, even though it is almost a kind of 'alien' life form", explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appears Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six major elements have been considered essential to life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But scientists found that the bacteria in Mono Lake, California, continue to grow even when they replace phosphorus with arsenic.
"You wonder what else is possible", said co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must identify life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study examines microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference that did not include details of the discovery prompted widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms in other planetary systems can use other elements to set off biochemical processes and that the 'standard elements' we believe are absolutely necessary for life are not necessarily fixed", explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another", Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she speculated that microbes exposed to both might be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is due primarily to its chemical similarity to phosphorus".
"It makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another".
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently from phosphorus, entering our biochemical system and smearing almost everything", Anbar explains.
The researchers exposed the GFAJ-1 to increasing levels of arsenic, and it adapted and grew.
The fact that the microbe thrives better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic, shows that arsenic-based life forms can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives us reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth", says Forster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
