The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The ruling came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was enough evidence to suggest that Ensign violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents first made public in the New York Times in October 2009 led to speculation that Ensign Douglas Hampton helped one of his campaign aides with lucrative contracts to buy his silence about an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
