Can politeness unite the divided?
After a campaign of swearing and negativity, little civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine bipartisan cooperation or a moment of illusion before returning quickly to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and top congressional officials failed to bring a breakthrough on the big issues that were being dealt with during the so-called lame duck session, the session at the end of a term in which no decisions are being made.
From what you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a respect for their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan point-scoring.
The public meeting of the President's deficit committee on Wednesday was equally civilised, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that masks the ideological divide that continues to separate members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - one demanding from the other a sign of cooperation and compromise, while the other is trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after another partisan war.
The meeting itself and the assessment of the meeting by the participants were therefore limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed in the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, donations, health care or neighborhood, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November election in Washington was at least briefly mild.
"No question, the tone has changed", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"That's inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that's good".
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution".
Bush's tax cuts are due to expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of it.
Both sides want to find a way to keep some or all of them, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe that they are favoring tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting at the White House on Tuesday, there was increased optimism that these issues could be agreed during the lame duck session and ratified at the same time as the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the "lame duck session" pressing issues may not necessarily lead to permanent party cooperation when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation", he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening between now and 2012 as a pre-fight, or shadow box, for the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who helped form it.
As concerned as Republican leaders may be about their high stakes, they know they have to try to keep their promises to cut government spending and roll back health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and reducing government spending.
The Vice-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and have, in their own judgment, pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 out of 18 votes in the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found among the elected representatives of the body, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little scope or sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will take place next year in the form of bipartisan clashes when Republicans challenge Obama on the state budget, taxes and health care system, followed later by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It's been proven that despite the bias in the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If a confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both sides must pay close attention to the public reaction.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarisation are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more consistent 2012 election.
In this way, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still separate them.
