The Popular Party won four congressional seats and the PSC lost nine.
The results of 28 November could play a decisive role for the PP in the cities of Lérida, Tarragona and Barcelona
After the significant increase in the number of votes and MPs in the last regional elections, the PP is already focusing its attention on the general elections, whether they are preferred or not.
The Catalan People's Party received 610,473 votes in the 2008 general elections, compared with 316,222 in the 2006 regional elections.
Last Sunday, the PPC won 384,091 votes.
If this upward trend - a result of the shift in the PSC's share of the vote and the PP's electorate's binding - continues, PP analysts predict that in the general election the PPC could rise from 8 to 12 congressmen, while CiU would also gain four (it now has 10) and the PSC would lose at least 9 (of 25) members.
These calculations show the fundamental importance of Catalonia for the PP and PSOE.
According to the analysis of the People's Party, the ERC would lose one member - currently it has three - while ICV could keep or gain one.
If the electoral calendar is maintained, however, the next date will be the municipal elections in May 2011, and even then the PP can be the tongue on the scale to end socialist dominance in four provincial capitals and with its majority in Barcelona city council, one of the municipalities with the largest budget: 661 million euros for 2011.
Both the Nationalists and the PP agree that the PSC will lose the cities of Barcelona, Tarragona, Lérida and Gerona, where the Socialists neither have a majority nor can rely on their traditional allies (ERC and ICV).
After the Republican debacle, it is not inconceivable that this party will lose its representation in the Barcelona city council, where it would have to win 5% of the vote.
The PP, on the other hand, saw its share of the vote increase in the four provincial capitals and could become a decisive force in Barcelona, Lérida and Tarragona.
The nationalists are convinced that they can play the leading role in the change in Tarragona, where they had governed with the PP before the current mayor, Josep Félix Ballesteros.
In Lérida, the PP is only 500 votes behind the PSC, and the mayor, Àngel Ros, has good relations with Mariano Rajoy, who met several times during the last election campaign.
The People's Party also saw significant growth in other important places, such as Badalona, Castelldefels and Reus.
The PP is currently represented in 34 municipalities in Catalonia and is seeking to form lists in as many places as possible.
The Catalan cell provided Al Qaeda with thousands of passports .
In addition to the seven arrests in Barcelona, there were three more in Thailand.
The seven Pakistanis and the Nigerian arrested by the Barcelona Police Intelligence Service were part of the Thai-led jihadist cell that provided passports to various al-Qaeda groups, including the Liberation Movement for Tamil Eelam (LTTE) and Laschkar e-Taiba (LET), the latter of which carried out the 2008 bombings in Mumbai that killed 106 people.
The Spanish Interior Minister attaches great importance to these investigations, going so far as to assure that Operation Kampai has "weakened" and "thereby impaired" the worldwide counterfeiting apparatus of Al Qaeda.
The researchers believe that during the two years the cell was active in Catalonia, thousands of passports were sent to Thailand, where they were forged and then sent to the groups that make up the criminal galaxy of Al Qaeda, so that their "fighters" could cross the borders of Europe and other Western countries with impunity.
The European Union has a responsibility to ensure that the terrorist group is not only the only one active in Europe, but also to ensure that the police of other countries are involved in the investigation, as well as the Thai police.
In coordination with this operation (Pakistani Junaid Humayun, Atiqur Rehman, Jabran Asghar, Malik Iftikhar Ahmad, Mohammad Saddique Khan Begum, Tanveer Arshad and Nigerian Babatunde Agunbiade were arrested), another was carried out in Thailand, in which Pakistanis Muhammad Athar Butt and Zeeshan Ehsan Butt and Thai Sirikanlaya Kijbumrung were arrested.
They had been in charge of the cell in Bangkok, and had been in Spain and other European countries.
The Catalan network, part of which was dismantled in 2009, stole passports from tourists in particular, following the guidelines of the so-called 'International Islamic Front'.
This meant that the documents had to be issued in the name of men aged 25 to 45 and had to be valid for several years; they were not allowed to have visa stamps.
Investigators have pointed out that no links have been established between the arrested in Catalonia and the bombing in Bombay, although the perpetrator of the bombing was Laschkar e-Taiba, one of the recipient groups of the passports stolen in Spain and then forged in Thailand.
Nevertheless, it should be remembered that several thousand dollars were sent from Catalonia via a money transfer company a few days before the attack, which were "invested" in the purchase of prepaid mobile phone cards, which were later used by members of the "commando" that killed 106 people.
The police have seized a large amount of documentation.
