Red Bull wins F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
The cars are being upgraded with real-time software.
Since Red Bull entered the world of Formula One in 2004, their story in this exquisite universe has been one of speed, surprise and success.
At first, no one paid attention to the newcomer and despite his steep rise during the last seasons, at the final sprint last November, everyone bet on the victory of Fernando Alonso's Ferrari.
Without wanting to belittle the skills of German driver and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of Renault's engine, the "secret weapon" that put the Multi Siemens Red Bull in the hands of the team and thus created a winning team has become legendary.
In fact, it is a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched in 2007 for non-car racing purposes.
This computer program, called PLM, has been used to develop assembly lines in factories around the world, power plants and high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce or simulate a product or process accurately before it is actually built, so as to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's cameras, Sukhoi's airplanes and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that using this software in the Formula 1 factory, Red Bull can design and implement the changes and improvements detected in the races and tests "in a matter of hours, almost in real time".
Russworm points out that in 1992 there were on average ten technicians working in the racetracks, who could make no more than three or four improvements in a season.
Today, the Red Bull team employs 180 highly qualified young people who use powerful computer equipment to perform analysis and any changes to the race car.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software was capable of analysing and improving all the components of Red Bull's racing cars, except for the engine, for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements are being changed.
The changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to the real world in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this crazy technical perfectionism is the 40 million dollars a Formula 1 team can spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has set up its high-tech factory for the development and production of its racing cars in a location 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially by journalists, are severely restricted.
Everything that happens in there is top secret.
The staff is 580 people, including the two pilots, world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true Formula One hero is undoubtedly the latest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
The enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts at its service to participate in the racetracks hide other protagonists whose support is invaluable and whose reputation is zero.
The plant's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, emphasizes that five years ago it was still possible to say that progress in R&D for racing cars contributed 50 percent to victory and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today, the stakes have changed, and technology is now 85 percent of success, while the contribution of pilots is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by computers because they "are not predictable gladiators".
