Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has decided to keep the euro, but at the same time it has set conditions for the whole European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a twofold response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has proposed new adjustment measures, ranging from tax cuts for small and micro-enterprises, regulation of temporary enterprises or the abolition of the 426 euro aid for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 per cent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 per cent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the Deputy Prime Minister, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is to be expected that Merkel's position is not a fault of her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is adopting a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the preservation of the long-standing traditions of many of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
Secondly, the reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment - is supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 per cent of the population.
The third is a restructuring of the euro in line with German proposals, which means more macroeconomic controls, strict budgetary management, sanctions for countries that fail to comply, possibly a suspension of payments in some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out of the sleeve of a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, Merkel has again taken a clear position in the last few days of October, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be rescued and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it fuelled the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
But their proposal, albeit a little sweeter, was accepted and in the coming months we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union which will make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures must be taken now - the old way of working of the euro will no longer exist from that date onwards.
2013 will be the birth of a new currency area where countries that fail to comply are severely punished, can be forced into insolvency and the private sector must bear some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we must set a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge gaps in the balance of payments, as was shown by Spain during boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we'd be bad at not understanding it.
It's not just about reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under those conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope the current turbulence will pass into a quieter atmosphere.
And that we will use the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after last Saturday's meeting with the big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of order in one's own house has made its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything will change.
The possibility of leaving the euro area, which is full of unreliable countries, is not to be excluded.
In that case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
