Tricks like Alonso and Ramos's against Ajax show ingenuity, but not the will to evade a penalty.
The alleged suspension of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has led to much speculation about whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is common knowledge, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and committed several fouls to get the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as Real Madrid would lead their group, the two players will meet the required penalty in the next league match against Auxerre and thus enter the next round without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the case is due to the fact that a team from the football club Real Madrid (which in its anthem pretends nobility and honor and on other occasions had punished its players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
The debate is, in any case, whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a circumvention of the rules.
The damage done to the spirit of sport should be examined in this matter.
The spirit of sport defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of fair play is to prevent the aggressor players from taking an unwarranted advantage of the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by cheating or circumventing the rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not done in secret to avoid a penalty, but it should be as obvious as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and accepted the penalty with joy.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders got from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasised that neither the opponent was put at a disadvantage nor were advantages claimed for the game played, as the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It's not a useful strategy for the next game, either, because the club doesn't have those players.
The advantage is obviously that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it's a long-term, to some extent uncertain advantage, because the team could eventually be eliminated, and the players who do this get a penalty and go into the second round, where they're eliminated with one less card than in the first round because of accumulation of cards.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
Finally, such practices are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which includes strategic decisions to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a penalty (which would in fact be a clear case of rule evasion), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or escaping punishment.
Although the line between ingenuity and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this case is a clear case of ingenuity.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it involved two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provocative rule transfer.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
Offering to attract customers for group Christmas dinners in Barcelona
The dictatorship of the calendar is causing an avalanche of reservations to fall this year on December 16 and 17.
The employee-owned parties are spreading, and they don't want to spend more than 20 to 30 euros.
Like the Turrón and the Christmas lottery, group dinners are also held in the run-up to Christmas, providing oxygen to Barcelona's restaurant and leisure industry, but as a result of the economic crisis, they are launching a price offensive to reach the mass segment of customers: almost everyone wants to spend between 20 and 30 euros for a lunch or dinner, the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations confirm.
To make the accounting a little more complicated, the calendar (New Year falls on a Friday) has dropped all orders into the week of December 13, resulting in an avalanche of dinner reservations on two peak days (the 16th and 17th) and almost no orders the week before.
Since 2008, when the bad times began, many companies have stopped group dinners for budgetary reasons.
In order to keep up with this tradition, many workers pay out of pocket.
Whatever the economic situation, the demand for minimum prices is high, says Gaietà Farràs, chairman of the Barcelona Restaurant Association.
The representative of the umbrella association has not yet dared to predict what the holidays will look like this month.
"People think twice before they book".
"They want to go out, but they are very pricey", he says.
Business will be good with those who "offer quality at good prices with good service", he adds, reminding us that customers save in times of crisis, which is why prices around 25 euros are the most demanded.
A survey of several downtown restaurants shows that the evening of December 17th led to the collapse of the restaurant chain.
The Soteras Group says demand for this Friday's offer will be booming with the intention of spending less than 30 euros, and the group has adapted its menus to the economic situation with full-service offers between 25 and 35 euros.
Another leading group, Andilana, which operates 16 restaurants in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), has had its own calendar, which has led to early reservations, even from the beginning of November.
"We have done the impossible to maintain the previous year's prices with menus for every taste from 19.95 to 30 euros", he explains.
AN Grup, which runs El Mussol, Attic, QuQu and 23 stores in total, is not losing its optimism after a second quarter of revenue recovery and a good outlook for Christmas sales, although concentrated on a few days.
Sources at the company point out that the 18th will also be an overactive day with groups of friends celebrating Christmas.
The six group menus have been supplemented by a Christmas menu for 30 euros or more as a price hit, giving the impression that customers are willing to spend 10 percent more than last year and want more details in return, such as cava.
In some companies, green shoots are also being seen sprouting, which is why the employees are invited back, giving the impression that the group meals are back on the rise.
On the other hand, the vice-president of the association Fecasarm (with associations such as the Barcelona Association of Pubs, Restaurants and Leisure) Enric Gomà is confident that this is the end of the tunnel and notes that the bookings are overall quite "vivid" although the customers "put out a maximum".
But the fun of the party didn't go away, no matter who paid.
Pakistan's nuclear program is a major concern in the United States.
Islamabad is building nuclear weapons "faster than any other country".
WikiLeaks leaks confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the North American embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department revealed by the Internet portal Wikileaks confirms the enormous concerns Washington has about Pakistan's nuclear program.
Beyond the revealing and juicy details provided by the documents on the content of the talks and the thinking of the accredited US diplomats in Islamabad, they reveal that cooperation between the two countries on nuclear security is not increasing but on the contrary "decreasing", and that the unstable Asian country is producing more nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country".
In particular, the peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but are stored in their individual parts to make it more difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is causing sleepless nights in Washington.
In a report prepared for the visit of former National Security Council chief James Jones, the Ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, listed the following risks: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the area under attack by the Taliban, the probable dispersal of nuclear material and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear material".
The large number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and missile programmes is no longer seen as a cause for alarm by the United States alone but also by Russia.
"Pakistan needs to hire hard-core personnel to guard the nuclear facilities; because of the low levels of education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit individuals involved in nuclear or missile programs", said Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev in a meeting with his North American counterparts.
What's new about the documentation leaked by Julian Assange's Internet portal is that the cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation is declining and the pace at which Pakistan is building nuclear weapons is increasing.
In May, an embassy office described communication with Pakistan as "frustrating": "There is often a lack of transparency; we do not receive responses to offers of assistance or they are rejected".
In another report, Peter Lavoy, a government intelligence official for South Asia, confirmed that "despite the economic disaster, Pakistan is building nuclear weapons at a rate no other country is able to".
Ambassador Patterson asks Washington to "clarify" to the official during a visit by the Supreme Commander, General Ashfaq Kayani, that "Pakistan's army must cease its tacit support for terrorist groups".
In the hunt for the WikiLeaks boss
Obama appoints a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further disclosures.
Interpol is issuing a red alert to track down and track down Assange.
Everything that has to do with WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, is a complicated maze in which the facts are difficult to unravel.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a "red alert" to "find and prosecute" Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
Besides, it's not new. It's from November 20th.
It has nothing to do with the recent leak of over four million US diplomatic documents, but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian has to face in Sweden.
The lawyer for the WikiLeaks founder, Mark Stephens, also said that "the police would know where and how to contact Mr Assange".
The International Police Authority, based in Lyon, France, issued the order on 20 December at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after the Swedish authorities had received the authorization.
The 188 countries of Interpol are instructed to identify and locate Assange, "in order to arrest him and extradite him".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual who has been subject to a red alert, many member countries consider the red alert a waiver for an arrest - which must be carried out by the national police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition treaty, as is the case in Sweden and the UK, where Assange is believed to be held.
The move outraged Assange's lawyers, who issued a letter informing them that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder was willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested permission to leave Sweden and was granted permission by the prosecutor, who is compared to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's head of security.
"This is like a hunt, not a legal pursuit", the letter charged.
While the world searches for him - and his mother from Australia insists her son is innocent - Assange is in an unknown location, but not silent.
On Monday, he gave a Skype interview to the editor of Time magazine from an undisclosed location, in which he asked for the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN, in violation of international agreements signed by the US, she should resign", he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called his resignation request "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not sure why we should care about the opinion of a guy with a website", he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, with preventing further leaks.
President Barack Obama's spokesman's attempt to turn a blind eye to Assange is contrary to the opinions being voiced by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House National Security Committee in January, has asked the State Department to consider putting WikiLeaks on a list of terrorist organizations "to seize their funds and prosecute anyone who supports or contributes to them".
Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone even further and had to retract his statement that Assange must be "murdered".
"Obama would have to turn it into a target and use a drone or something".
The one who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and a potential presidential candidate.
"Whoever leaked information to the government is guilty of treason and anything that is not an execution is too lenient a punishment", he told Fox.
Puigcercós seeks peace in the ERC with a wink to the Carod
The Republican leader allows the party a secret vote on his continued tenure.
Huguet proposes a more pluralistic government and the end of the principle of the plenary assembly.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe to avoid an internal upheaval for the tenth time in the ranks of the ERC, which is without direction after losing 11 MPs and half the votes.
The party leader is aware that his threat to resign is not enough for the people close to former party leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that the influence of this sector is today as weakened as their mentor himself and will not give him the same headaches as other former currents.
The leader of Esquerra is therefore trying to win over the new critics with a wink, which would secure his position until the next local elections.
For starters, yesterday announced that the more than 200 regional council members of ERC could speak in secret about his continued tenure.
With ballots, not with a raised hand.
If the Carodists wanted to give the president a ticket, they could do so without fear of reprisals.
In fact, the boss wants to avoid the impression of division as well as submission to his person.
In several interviews, he confirmed that he would not feel confirmed with half the votes plus one, and he added without giving percentages that a result "Bulgarian style" would not be good either.
Carod's associates are demanding more from the president than just giving his office to the party, an inadequate gesture given Puigcercós' control of the highest organ of Congress.
But since they don't have a majority to force resignations, they'll agree a plan of action with the board between now and May.
The Commission is also proposing to increase the number of EU Member States' national authorities to include the European Union in the list of countries with the highest number of registered EU citizens.
Their intention is to vouch for Puigcercós, in return for which he promises to postpone the congress to the fall of 2011, which the party leadership already considers a fact.
The ERC party chairman believes that 'polyphony' is harmful to stability and he is striving once and for all to enable the organisation to wash its dirty laundry behind closed doors.
In this sense, the article signed by the acting Councillor Josep Huguet in his blog is symptomatic.
Given that Puigcercós is an ideologue, the owner of Innovació considered it a fact that the party leader was supported "in exchange for different goals".
He listed five, two of which are in the foreground.
First, the "restructuring" of the board so that it represents at least 90 percent of the party members, that is, the inclusion of new faces from Carod's circle.
The second one could be the big news.
Huguet proposes that the ERC finally abandon the principle of the plenary assembly as a mode of operation.
He is therefore advocating a reform of the statutes to allow elected delegates to hold the congresses.
Puigcercós' team, which has been fighting for it in the last two congresses, is obsessed with ending the assembly model - an exception in the Spanish party system.
In fact, at the eventful 2008 assembly, the party leadership was tasked with reviewing the principle of the General Assembly at a congress to discuss the reform of the statutes.
The Commission has not yet decided on this date, as the internal unrest of recent years has made it unwise to take this matter up.
Now that critical sectors are not on the lookout, it may be time to take this matter up again and close it for good.
