China maintains its targets for reducing greenhouse gases
The Chinese representative stated at COP16 that his country had made tremendous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is keeping its promise to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and transform its industry.
He pointed out that in the last four years his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
He said China would not change its objectives but would work with the international community on the issue.
He explained that China's climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
He said progress had been made in all aspects, including the adoption last year of a new energy law which included targets for reducing emissions.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states had worked together with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction.
The Commission established the profitability of the sampled Union producers by expressing the pre-tax net profit of the sales of the like product to unrelated customers in the Union as a percentage of the turnover of those sales.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which has been implemented over the past five years and has received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private sources.
He said a project on climate change at the provincial level, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving ones and another on mitigation and adaptation was under way.
Martin Krol, a scientific adviser to the government on climate change in that country, confirmed that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly believed.
He pointed out that per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States they are 100 tons. China is responsible for nine percent of total pollution.
He also said that the EU was making unprecedented progress in energy efficiency, which had increased by 20 per cent in the last five years and was set to increase again by 2020.
