Obama on Twitter advocates for law to help undocumented students
"If you are in favor of the Dream Act, call your senators and urge the passage of this law", the president of the United States tweeted on the popular social network.
President Barack Obama today supported the nationwide mobilization in support of the Dream Act - a bill to legalize undocumented students - with a message on his personal Twitter blog.
"If you're for the Dream Act, call your senators and push for the passage of this bill", Obama tweeted.
His brief includes a cyberlink to a larger document urging the public to contact their senators immediately as the vote on the bill is imminent.
"With your voice we have been waiting for, the time has come to listen to you", he emphasizes.
The news spread after the 42 Republican senators threatened to block any vote on any bill unless the Bush-era tax cuts were extended and government funding expanded.
Such a blockade, announced in a letter signed by the 42 Republican senators, could affect the passage of the Dream Act and other bills, such as ratification of the new START nonproliferation treaty with Russia.
Asked about the Republican blockade of the Dream Act and other bills, presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs said he was confident that once the tax issue was resolved, a timetable could be drawn up for the remaining bills.
"I think we have plenty of time...
"We all agree that the tax issue must be resolved before the end of the year"...
"I think we can reach an agreement on this at any time and then we can plan the rest", he said.
Senate Democratic Majority Leader Harry Reid announced on Tuesday that he would "make a request for a vote at the end of the debate" so that the Dream Act, which would legalize undocumented students, could be voted on in the Senate starting next Thursday, though it is more likely to be next week.
The version of the Dream Act or the American Dream Act would legalize about 800,000 young people who immigrated to the United States before they were sixteen, who have lived in this country for the past five years, and who are enrolled in a higher education institution or in the military.
But the bill's proponents need sixty votes to pass the initiative, so they rely on the votes of a handful of Republicans.
The Democrats, who are in the majority in favor of the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However, one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote against it and only one Republican, Richard Lugar of Indiana, has announced his support for the bill.
That's why the Dream Act's advocates need to get more Republicans on their side in case other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the initiative.
Among the most sought-after Republicans are Maine's Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, as well as Senator George Lemieux of Florida, who took over from Senator Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who have supported the Dream Act in the past include Orrin Hatch of Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but they have stated they will no longer support it on another occasion.
Another Republican who had spoken out in favor of the bill, John McCain, has not yet made his position known.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the Dream Act faces the biggest obstacles in the Senate.
Putting Literature in the Wound
The second round of 'The Lust for Language' was a walk where participants were encouraged to tell stories
"I understand the sex in language, but... the finger in the wound? What is expected of me?" asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela, who was to open the second round of 'Los placeres de la lengua', a cycle celebrating Spanish-language literature and using the subtitle of her question on this occasion (at another event, the round table was dedicated to sex in language, she explained).
The finger in the wound... "is getting us into trouble", the Argentine writer spat sweetly at the audience, which was mainly young people, who had gathered at the International Book Fair in Guadalajara (FIL) to attend the roundtable moderated by Marisol Shultz, which included Valenzuela, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Montero and Luis García Montero.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text she dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, which Shultz later described as a great story. Luisa is the first-person narrator and protagonist who is searching to find out what a "wound" is, and goes from doctor to doctor, from whom she receives no answer, but clues to guide her story.
She leaves the infectious disease doctors convinced that "patience is not my strength, perhaps it is my wound".
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the trauma specialist, who took her breath away in the middle of the hallway, but who explained that wound was not a scientific concept, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "the wound is the really open, the symbolic is the scar".
The main character sighs with relief, concluding that she "only learned from the wound that it was really open and did not exist".
Valenzuela, the writer, played with them both.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful story, which he called 'Praise to the Invention', in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned but discovered.
With allusions to magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched the clouds, brought back men who had traveled far, or restored the virtue lost by a girl. The tale turned around and told of America, the great novel that from the beginning was not lacking in its own chronicler, and he quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo, who criticized the abundance of stories told by the conquerors.
"Cervantes, who invited us all [the writers], mocked the false witnesses who appeared in the stories presented as true, but otherwise the history of America would never have been told - with imagination that even the sense of shame was gone".
However, he points out that "it is the madmen and liars who imagine things best", and that is where reality and lies converge, where one no longer knows which side of the narrative to belong to, where fiction reaches its peak.
He actually calls it the Cervantes tradition.
"From him we inherit what is told".
When Mayra Montero was next on the panel, the writer commented on and praised the variety of interpretations that the FIl's invitation to the 'Finger in the Wound' round table had contributed to.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican women dedicated their contribution to the great wound of social violence that their country - like all Latin America - is suffering as a result of the fight against drug trafficking.
"I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs involve a tacit, unintentionally planned commitment", she explained, after pointing out that literature is communication and bonding that builds between the author and the reader as in a "chemical reaction".
The evening was decided by the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose contribution also highlighted "that finger of the committed writer in the writer's wound".
He noted that in a fast-paced world, even intellectual habits and mind controls are reduced to dogmatism, forgetting "that behind every affirmation is a little no and behind every denial a little yes".
"To be in possession of our thoughts and reality, we must nuance: and nuance often means putting our finger in the wound and harassing those who feel much more comfortable thinking in the form of caricatures, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuance, and also harassing the powerful who prefer to divide the world into black and white", he observed, inviting us to rediscover the meaning of writing.
Romano fighting for his first title
Rubén Omar Romano looks back on three defeats in the finals, he has had ups and downs in his career, but he played three decisive games.
In the final match between Santos Laguna and Monterrey, two different styles are also facing each other, defined by their respective coaches, and their contrasting encounter is reflected in the results.
Rubén Omar Romano looks back on three defeats in the finals, he has had ups and downs in his career, but three decisive games, and so far he has been holding up well, which is why this opportunity is very important for him.
The Argentine has won the second championship, he is one step behind the winners and surprisingly he has played consecutive finals with the same team.
The Santista strategist reached his first final as a coach at the 2002 Torneo Apertura, when del Morelia had the reins in hand, with which he suffered a big defeat against Toluca with 4-2; later, at the Clausura 2003, he reached the decisive duel, which he also lost with 3-1 against Rayados.
Already with Santos Laguna at the 2010 Torneo Bicentenario, where they played against Los Diablos, Rubén had to take another setback as the game ended in a 2-2 draw against Los Choriceros after 210 minutes of play, but at the eleventh-yard line he came up 3-1 and had two chances to clinch his title, but in the end three of his players missed the eleven steps and the game turned into a 4-3.
