The main problem, the 1.8 billion tonnes of CFCs emitted by lighting, would be avoided if the white light bulbs, which still have a 50-70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or, better still, LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the global vehicle fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters of emissions, including the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 to 49 gt.
However, 5 Gt would still have to be deducted from this balance to stabilise the rise in climate by 2 degrees Celsius between now and 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-glowing bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produces light.
The compact fluorescent bulbs reduce energy consumption by 75%, and the new LED bulbs reduce this energy consumption by a further twofold.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched this week by Philips, a company that participated in the UN study, have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than a white light bulb, which is a sign of the savings potential of the replacement plan, which is to be implemented in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new bulbs emit very little heat, they can also operate with a regulating resistance.
