Several experts have pointed out that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the manufacturers provide a receiving point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-lit bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the benefits that each country would derive from this international programme.
