Vengeful Hackers and Hardworking Spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal which is merely a scandal in the sinful hypocrisy which governs the relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level and gives a foretaste of a future dominated by recession.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence service (any nation) is composed entirely of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what you read for months in any journal (except the ones owned by Berlusconi), and the gruesome caricature of Gaddafi's profile has long provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches.
The rule that secret files must only consist of news already known is essential to the dynamics of intelligence services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will find that each work (on the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not merely because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the nonexistent), but because those who practice the occult believe only in what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is Dan Brown's success mechanism.
So is the secret market.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in mind) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, an editor at Libération), who only accepts as true what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the one Newsweek had published the week before.
So why has there been such a stir over the revelations of these files?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, that embassies - at least since the end of World War II, and since then even heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representative tasks, have become spy centers.
Any viewer of detective films knows this very well, and it is not hypocrisy that makes you pretend to ignore it.
However, the fact that it is being repeated publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that an X-rated hacker could tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal also causes distress not to the victims but to the "executioners".
But let's get to the deep nature of what happened.
Back in the day, in Orwell's time, you could pool all power like a Big Brother, controlling every move of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have been completely true since then, where you could control every move you make with your phone, every transaction you make, the hotel you visit, the highway you choose, and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
But when you consider what's happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control loop ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker -- chosen as the citizen's avenger -- can unlock the secrets of power.
But how can a power survive if it can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secrets, because it reveals the public sphere; but WikiLeaks-style revealing that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means depriving them of all power.
WikiLeaks did not wrong Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will be the consequences of this insult to such a powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer put any confidential information online - that would be like a street poster.
But it is equally obvious that with current technology, it is futile to hope to keep confidential reports over the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state has been on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future, and only for certain ears?
I know that my prediction sounds like science fiction and romance right now, but I find myself forced to imagine the government agents, secretly busy moving in uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages nowhere but in their mere memory, and beyond that, hiding the few written pieces of information they've been given in their shoe socks.
The information would be stored in a single copy in a sealed box: basically, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is advancing like a cancer these days, which is backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with (telephone) wires.
The (analogue) videocassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, by rewinding it from back to front and revealing all the secrets of editing, while the (digital) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, in macro proportions.
High-speed trains take three hours to travel from Rome to Milan, while air travel, including the changeover, takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communications technology to return to the car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is making good on its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to review the implementation of fast-start pledges (also known as 'fast start' or early financing) by developing countries.
And the French beauty parlours are exposed.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, developing countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU has been pulling up all the stocks to convince its partners of its commitment to fast start funding: detailed progress reports from its Member States, press conferences, major side events, distribution of brochures.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its very value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same thing at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has committed €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look in detail, things are a little more complicated.
This money should be 'new and additional' according to the Copenhagen Treaty to ensure that additional investment is made without detriment to official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline he or she considers best.
The EU Commission, for example, has chosen to set the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained and 150 million will be added over three years under the 'Start-up' financing.
Other countries have adopted similar guidelines, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considered that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 was 'new and additional'.
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the previous year's expenditure or for global public development aid.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to be in compliance with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into grants and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses his own calculation mode.
Some, such as France, consider 1 € borrowed to be equivalent to 1 € donated.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emissions-controlled projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is misleading to present the euro as the equivalent of a donated euro.
But France has no other reasoning than to "respect" its €420 million commitment by borrowing 91.5% (€389.8 million) and donating 8.5% (€36.1 million) - see also the EU document to see for yourself.
France is the only EU country that makes large use of loans.
Germany claims 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) are fulfilling their obligations 100% through donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and means a comparable investment.
That's a good hocus-pocus.
In the first place, the Commission has already made a number of proposals to the Council and the Council for the establishment of a European Investment Bank.
France succeeds in making it appear that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Treasury (as it seems that Bercy was the one who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; firstly, internally (why do the other member states continue to donate when they can only borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries cannot be completely fooled...
The chapter on early finance is only a small issue in a relatively short time compared to the whole of the climate debate.
But it could be the drop too much in the vast machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is imperative that he learn his lesson from this first year of early financing.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and of balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could bring forward the debate on the subject of longterm financing (another crucial and currently debated topic): the question of the 'accountability' or the way its loans are accounted for cannot be escaped.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
The hope is therefore in the new environment minister, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's Fast Start and its vision of 'accountability' and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly the movement for the protection of the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which states that its results 'in view of the small number of samples analysed do not represent a statistically significant value but are rather illustrative of the problem being dealt with', bought between July and September the food normally consumed in four meals, by a child of about ten years of age, plus a snack, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products, and a pint of water a day - have been tested by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and other contaminants, as have sweets.
The balance sheet is staggering: 81 chemicals, including 42 classified as potentially or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 endocrine disruptors, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded in the vast majority of cases, this survey shows very well that the reality of the consumer's exposure to potentially carcinogenic substances or endocrine disrupting substances is a cause for concern", the association notes.
Already at breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three of those that are certainly carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including at lunchtime, in which the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
Also, the chopped steak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the gum were spiked with pesticides and other chemicals.
The analysis of the tap water revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 identified chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not uncontaminated.
The ultimate risk of this "pollutant cocktail" to the consumer "is likely to be underestimated", says the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed, 'in view of the urgency of the situation', a moratorium on the use of pesticides to halt the 'increase in diseases of civilization'.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
